web_results.snippet: Tilia is a genus of about 30 species of trees or bushes, native throughout most of the temperate Northern Hemisphere. The tree is known as linden for the European species, and basswood for North American species.

related_questions.question: What is linden?
related_questions.snippet: Linden is a common name for trees belonging to the Tilia genus. The dried flower, leaves, and wood are used for medicine. People use linden for conditions such as colds, headache, trouble sleeping (insomnia), itchy skin, and many others, but there is no good scientific evidence to support these uses.

related_questions.question: What is linden good for?
related_questions.snippet: These flowers were steeped as a tea to relieve anxiety related to indigestion, irregular heartbeat, and vomiting. Today, linden is used in many cough and cold remedies. Active ingredients in linden help promote sweating, which may help treat people with fevers.

related_questions.question: What is special about linden trees?
related_questions.snippet: Linden trees are a large tree that has about 30 different species and types. While they also grow to be quite tall, they have a very long lifespan as well. Most have a lifespan of several hundred years but there are some Linden trees that have lived thousands of years as well.

related_questions.question: What does the name linden mean?
related_questions.snippet: Meaning:Linden tree. Parents foraging for unique arboreal names will love the Germanic gender-neutral title, Linden. This verdurous name means “linden tree” and is a tree with heart-shaped leaves belonging to the Tilla genus. Linden speaks like a breath of fresh air and brings idyllic meadows and forests to mind.

buttons.subtitle: How Fast Does A Linden Tree Grow
buttons.title: June 2024 - Silver Linden | Princeton, NJ
buttons.snippet: In youth, the tree can grow 1 to 2 feet per year. Sun: Silver Linden trees need 2–6 hours of direct sunlight each day but can also tolerate partial shade. Soil: Linden trees can tolerate a wide range of soil conditions, but they prefer moist, well-drained, fertile, loamy soil with a neutral to alkaline pH.

buttons.subtitle: How To Care For Tilia
buttons.title: Caring for Your Littleleaf Linden (Tilia cordata): Tips for a Healthy
buttons.snippet: Tilia cordata prefers full sun to partial shade, so choose a spot in your yard that gets at least 4 hours of sunlight per day. The tree is adaptable to a wide range of soils, but prefers moist, well-drained soil. Be sure to give your tree plenty of room to grow, as it can reach heights of 40-50 feet. Water regularly.
snippet_highlighted_words: choose a spot in your yard that gets at least 4 hours of sunlight per day

buttons.subtitle: What Are The Uses Of Tilia

buttons.snippet: Tilia cordata, also known as small-leaved lime, is considered the most potent species of the Tilia genus (1). Linden tea has been used in folk medicine across cultures to relieve high blood pressure, calm anxiety, and soothe digestion. To create this herbal infusion, flowers, leaves, and bark are boiled and steeped.

buttons.subtitle: Tilia Lifespan
buttons.title: Linden tree: growing & caring for Tilia trees - Plantura Magazin
buttons.snippet: Linden trees grow between 15 and 40 metres high, depending on their species and variety, and can live for over 1000 years. This is in part due to their ability to resprout, even after damage and disease. The leaves of many linden species are heart-shaped, which is why linden trees are also called trees of love.

buttons.subtitle: How To Plant Tilia
buttons.title: Littleleaf Linden Tree - McKay Nursery
buttons.snippet: The best time for planting a linden tree is in fall after the leaves drop, although you can plant container-grown trees any time of year. Choose a location with full sun or partial shade and moist, well-drained soil. The tree prefers a neutral to alkaline pH but tolerates slightly acidic soils as well.
snippet_highlighted_words: The best time for planting a linden tree is in fall after the leaves drop
